  <h2>What is Text-to-Speech and Why Use It?</h2>
  <p>Text-to-speech (TTS) converts written text into natural-sounding spoken audio. It's useful for accessibility, learning, content consumption, and productivity.</p>

  <p>Common use cases:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Proofreading documents by ear (catch errors your eyes miss)</li>
    <li>Accessibility for visually impaired users</li>
    <li>Listening to articles while driving or exercising</li>
    <li>Language learning and pronunciation practice</li>
    <li>Creating audio demos or voice-overs</li>
    <li>Converting blog posts to audio content</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How to Convert Text to Voice Online</h2>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Paste or type your text</strong> — Paste from a document or type directly into our <a href="/tools/text-to-voice/">text to voice converter</a>.</li>
    <li><strong>Select a voice</strong> — Choose from 50+ available voices including Google neural voices, system voices, and natural-sounding options.</li>
    <li><strong>Adjust speed and pitch</strong> — Slow down for clarity (90 WPM) or speed up (150 WPM). Adjust pitch from deep to high.</li>
    <li><strong>Click Play</strong> — Listen instantly. Our <a href="/tools/text-to-voice/">free TTS tool</a> uses your device's speakers.</li>
    <li><strong>Record if needed</strong> — Use your device's built-in audio recorder to save the output as MP3.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Getting More and Better Voices</h2>

  <h3>On Windows</h3>
  <p>Settings → Time & Language → Speech → Manage Voices. Click "Download more voices" to add Microsoft neural voices like Aria, Guy, Zira, and others.</p>

  <h3>On Mac</h3>
  <p>System Settings → Accessibility → Spoken Content → Manage Voices. Click the download button next to available voices (Samantha, Karen, Moira, etc.).</p>

  <h3>On Chrome</h3>
  <p>Chrome automatically includes Google's neural voices (like Google UK English Female) on supported platforms. These high-quality voices sound natural and conversational.</p>

